# Teamwork product workflow (FOS Dashboard)

Teamwork project: **FOS Dashboard Development** (`win.godeap.io`, project id `1615262`). Operating model: `docs/teamwork-workflow.md`. Manifest: `docs/teamwork-manifest.json`.

## Source of truth by phase

| Phase | Authoritative spec | Git role |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Draft / In review | **Teamwork notebook** | Do not overwrite `docs/features/*.md` from git-first drafts |
| Approved for implementation | **Teamwork notebook** | **Sync notebook to git** before coding |
| In development | Teamwork notebook (frozen); git working copy | Implement from synced `docs/features/*.md` |
| Shipped | Teamwork notebook + task | **Re-sync notebook to git** in the same commit as `FOS_PRD_VERSION` bump |

## Before starting implementation

1. Confirm the release task exists in Teamwork (name: `Feature NNN - ...` or legacy `vX.Y.Z - ...`) and is **Approved for implementation** or later.
2. Confirm linked notebook URLs are in the task description (`docs/teamwork-manifest.json` may list ids).
3. **Sync** the approved notebook content into the matching `docs/features/0NN-*.md` file. Do not code from a stale git spec if Teamwork was updated.
4. If the customer edited the notebook after approval, reconcile via the notebook **Change requests** section before coding, or defer changes to a follow-on release.

## During implementation

- Do not treat git feature docs as authoritative over Teamwork until synced from Teamwork.
- Post-approval customer edits belong in notebook **Change requests**; merge into the main spec body at ship, not ad hoc in git alone.
- Engineering-only detail (file paths, cache schema versions, FR/AC numbers) may be added in git **Technical appendix** or `*-implementation-plan.md` without replacing customer-facing notebook sections.
- One Teamwork task = one release. Do not combine unrelated scope in a single version bump.

## Ship checklist (required with every merge-worthy release)

1. Code + tests/smoke as usual; `clasp push` when deploying Apps Script.
2. Bump PRD per `google-apps-script-core.mdc` (`FOS_PRD_VERSION`, changelog, `src/*` headers). Version is chosen **here**, not at task intake.
3. **Rename** Teamwork release task to `vX.Y.Z - {title}` where `X.Y.Z` matches `FOS_PRD_VERSION` exactly (full task name = **release name**).
4. Run `python3 scripts/teamwork_ship_task.py --version-from-codejs --manifest-task ... --update-manifest` to set **Release Version** (`57879`), **Feature ID** (`57880`), **Release Type** (`57881`), and **Estimated Dev Hours** (`57883`; auto-estimated from git diff unless `--est-dev-hours` is passed), and move the task to workflow stage **Shipped**. Ensure manifest task has `featureId` and `releaseType` from intake.
5. **Export/sync** linked Teamwork notebook pages into `docs/features/*.md` (and implementation plan if maintained in Teamwork).
6. Update `docs/teamwork-manifest.json` task `shippedVersion`, rename manifest task key to final task name, notebook `lastSyncedAt`, and `workflowStage: Shipped` if ids are known.
7. Update `docs/features/000-overview.md` shipped line when the product version changes.

`teamwork_ship_task.py` moves the release task to workflow stage **Shipped** automatically (no separate manual step).

## Ship command (agent deliverable)

When feature work is **ready to ship** (or the user asks how to ship), the agent MUST provide a copy-paste command block generated by:

```bash
python3 scripts/teamwork_ship_command.py --feature-id NNN
```

Use `--manifest-task "..."` when feature id is unknown. Run the helper from repo root after `FOS_PRD_VERSION` is bumped; paste its output verbatim for the user (include the comment lines). Do not paraphrase flags or guess the manifest task key.

## New feature requests (pipeline)

1. Customer creates or requests work in Teamwork (task or message); product creates a **feature notebook** from `docs/FEATURE_TEMPLATE.md`.
2. Create release task `Feature NNN - ...` (no version prefix) in the correct **functional area task list**; link notebook(s) in description.
3. **Inbox intake (mandatory):** when the feature originates from the **Inbox** task list, move the new release task from **Backlog** to **Spec Draft** (`workflowId` **83492**, `stageId` **389189**) and set custom fields **Feature ID** (`57880`) and **Release Type** (`57881`: `Enhancement` or `Bug Fix`). Use `scripts/teamwork_intake.py` `create_release_task()`.
4. Customer review in Teamwork until **Spec Approved** (sync notebook to git before coding).
5. Sync notebook to git, then create or update `*-implementation-plan.md` and phase tasks if needed.
6. Implement, ship, sync git, tag task with final version.

## Bug-fix releases

- Patch tasks use the same model (`v2.12.5 - ...`).
- Link parent feature notebook; add **Release notes** (problem, fix, benefit) in notebook or task description.
- Sync release notes to PRD changelog; full feature notebook rewrite not required.

## Risk mitigations (mandatory)

| Risk | Rule |
| --- | --- |
| Notebook and git drift | Sync at **approval** and again at **ship**; never only at ship if coding already started |
| Cursor implements stale spec | Run notebook-to-git sync before first line of feature code |
| Customer rewrites AC during dev | Freeze at approval; post-approval edits only in **Change requests** until ship |
| Task version name wrong after scope change | Use `Feature NNN - title` until ship; rename once at deploy to match `FOS_PRD_VERSION` |
| Version guessed at intake | Do not put `vX.Y.Z` in task title until ship; optional `workingVersionEstimate` in manifest only |
| Manual sync forgotten | Ship checklist blocks completion until git reflects Teamwork |
| Dual maintenance burden | Customer prose in Teamwork; technical appendix in git; link both in manifest |

## Do not

- Create new `docs/features/0NN-*.md` specs as the first step when the user asked for Teamwork-first workflow (notebook leads unless explicitly syncing from existing git).
- Mark Teamwork task Shipped without PRD version bump and git doc sync in the same delivery.
- Expose `TEAMWORK_BEARER_TOKEN` or copy secrets into docs or manifest.
